note_text: A 52-year-old male presents to the ED with severe epigastric pain radiating to the back, nausea, and vomiting for the past 12 hours. History significant for heavy alcohol use and fatty food consumption the night before. Vital signs: T 38.2°C, BP 135/85 mmHg, HR 102 bpm. Physical exam reveals epigastric tenderness with guarding. Labs show lipase 1200 U/L, amylase 450 U/L, WBC 16,500/μL, Ca 7.8 mg/dL, BUN 45 mg/dL. CT abdomen shows pancreatic inflammation with peripancreatic fluid and no evidence of gallstones. Patient admitted for acute pancreatitis management.

note_text: A 45-year-old female presents to the emergency department with acute onset of severe chest pain radiating to the left arm, which started 2 hours ago while at rest. The pain is described as crushing and is associated with shortness of breath, nausea, and profuse sweating. Patient has a history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Vital signs show BP 160/95 mmHg, HR 102 bpm, RR 24/min, O2 sat 94% on room air. Physical examination reveals an anxious patient in acute distress. Cardiac examination shows regular rhythm with S4 gallop. ECG shows ST-segment elevation in leads V1-V4. Initial troponin I is elevated at 2.3 ng/mL. Patient was immediately taken to the cardiac catheterization lab where 100% occlusion of the left anterior descending artery was found and successfully treated with PCI and stent placement.

note_text: A 72-year-old male with a history of COPD presents with worsening shortness of breath over the past 3 days. He reports increased cough with greenish sputum production and wheezing. He has been using his rescue inhaler more frequently with minimal relief. Current smoker with 40 pack-year history. Vital signs: T 38.2°C, BP 138/88 mmHg, HR 92 bpm, RR 24/min, O2 sat 88% on room air. Physical exam reveals increased work of breathing with accessory muscle use, diffuse wheezing, and prolonged expiratory phase. Chest X-ray shows hyperinflation and patchy infiltrates in the right lower lobe. ABG shows pH 7.32, PaCO2 48 mmHg, PaO2 58 mmHg.

note_text: A 34-year-old female presents with sudden onset severe abdominal pain in the right lower quadrant that started 12 hours ago. The pain started periumbilically and migrated to the RLQ. She reports nausea, vomiting, and loss of appetite. No diarrhea or urinary symptoms. Last menstrual period was 2 weeks ago. Vital signs: T 38.1°C, BP 122/76 mmHg, HR 88 bpm, RR 18/min. Physical exam reveals rebound tenderness and guarding in the RLQ, positive McBurney's point tenderness. WBC count is 14,500/μL with neutrophilia. CT abdomen shows enlarged appendix with surrounding inflammation. Patient was taken to surgery for laparoscopic appendectomy.

note_text: A 68-year-old female presents with acute onset left-sided weakness and difficulty speaking that started 45 minutes ago while watching TV. Past medical history includes hypertension, atrial fibrillation (not on anticoagulation), and hyperlipidemia. Vital signs: BP 178/95 mmHg, HR 88 irregular, RR 16/min, O2 sat 98%. NIHSS score is 14. Physical exam reveals left facial droop, dysarthria, left hemiparesis (2/5 strength upper and lower extremities), and left sensory deficit. CT head without contrast shows no hemorrhage. CT perfusion reveals salvageable penumbra in the right MCA territory. tPA was administered followed by mechanical thrombectomy.
